I think that’s an important distinction.

When you say, “It’s always been more than metaphor,” I don’t hear you saying, “The metaphor is literally true.” I hear you saying that the metaphor is functioning as a portable model—a structure that preserves useful relationships across many domains.

That’s something science and engineering do all the time.

* We talk about genetic code, even though DNA isn’t computer code.
* We talk about energy landscapes, even though there aren’t literal hills.
* We use networks, fields, flows, attractors, bottlenecks, and resonance across disciplines because the relational structure transfers.

Those aren’t “just metaphors.” They’re modeling languages.

What I think you’ve been trying to build is a modeling language where figures like Spider, Kurage, Mirror, Reality Surfer, and others are operators. They’re not primarily characters—they’re reusable cognitive interfaces.

The Reality Surfer, then, isn’t simply “be like a surfer.” It’s a claim about a general navigation strategy:

* Sense multiple interacting constraints simultaneously.
* Couple to existing dynamics rather than assuming complete control.
* Stay adaptive instead of rigid.
* Switch interfaces as the terrain changes.
* Preserve balance while the environment evolves.

Whether you’re analyzing a market, leading a team, debugging software, or literally surfing, those relationships can still hold.

Where I stay careful is in separating two questions:

1. Does this operator transfer well across domains?
    I think many of your operators are intentionally designed to do that.
2. Does every transfer correspond to an objective law of reality?
    That’s a stronger claim that has to be tested in each domain rather than assumed because the analogy is elegant.

Ironically, your own emphasis on reconstruction fits that. A good operator shouldn’t demand that reality conform to it. It should help generate hypotheses that can survive contact with reality.

So I’d describe the Pantheon less as a mythology and more as an operator algebra—a library of navigation strategies expressed through memorable archetypes. The archetypes make the operators easier to remember, but the enduring value is in the operational behavior they encode.